{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":4398,"record_hash":"sha256:18d66ff95551a69196b965d89374080633a889b385fdccfbf7e70e34e26d7b9e","timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:26:36.774Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 6a4f17\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 512\nOutput:\n\nUse `skim` first when the goal is to recover enough turn history to continue:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog skim\nbut agentlog skim branch main\n```\n\n`skim` is intentionally a porcelain command. It loads all related matches,\nsorts sessions chronologically, and returns a compact table-of-contents entry\nfor every turn in every related session. JSON keeps full session/turn handles\nfor follow-up reads. Do not call this \"full context\"; it is the related turn\nhistory in abbreviated form.\n\nUse the drill-down commands when `skim` is too thin, ambiguous, missing the\nwhy, or the exact transcript detail matters. Do not start by dumping full\nrecords; skim should be enough for orientation.\n\n1. Start from a target and skim all related sessions in chronological order.\n2. If the human skim is enough, stop.\n3. If detail is needed, rerun skim as JSON to get `session_key` / `turn_key`.\n4. Hydrate bounded records only for the turn that needs detail.\n\nExample:\n\n```sh\nbut --json agentlog skim branch main\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --limit 20\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --limit 50\n```\n\nThe goal is orientation first, payload later. Do not start by dumping full\nrecords for every related session; that loses the signal these commands are\ntrying to preserve.\n\nThe old `sessions` command is hidden compatibility/debugging surface now.\nNormal agent recovery should be `skim`, then JSON `skim` plus `show` only when\nexact detail is needed.\n\n### Target Discovery\n\nWhen the user says \"current branch\" or gives no explicit target, inspect\nGitButler state first:\n\n```sh\nbut status\n```\n\nIf plain Git reports `gitbutler/workspace`, do not use that as the agentlog\nbranch target. Use `but status` to find the applied GitButler branch/stack name,\nthen query:\n\n```sh\nbut --json agentlog skim branch <gitbutler-branch-name>\n```\n\nRunning `but agentlog skim` without an explicit target performs this\nGitButler branch discovery automatically. Pass an explicit target when working\nfrom a review or change rather than the applied branch.\n\n### Reading `show`\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:26:36.774Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}